STREPTOCOCCUS GROUP A, SCARLET FEVER - CHINA (12): (GUANGDONG, HONG
KONG, MACAU)
*********************************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 10 Aug 2011
Source: Macau Daily Times [edited]
http://www.macaudailytimes.com.mo/macau/29416-Scarlet-fever-cases-dropping.html


Macau recorded 87 cases of scarlet fever up until yesterday [9 Sep
2011], a significant increase compared to the 16 cases last year
[2010], according to figures from the Health Bureau. Director of the
bureau Lei Chin Ion gave assurances at a press conference yesterday
that the situation is under control. "Cases are dropping, and there
was no significant increase after the re-opening of schools. No cases
of death were reported either," Lei said.

Scarlet fever is an illness potentially fatal among children. Hong
Kong declared an outbreak in June [2011], and 2 children died from
scarlet fever this year [2011] in the neighbouring territory. Unlike
Macau, the HKSAR [Hong Kong Special Administrative Region] has
reported an increase after the new school year commenced last week.

The head of Hong Kong's Department of Health (DP), Lam Ping Yan, told
reporters there were more than 1100 cases this year [2011]. He pledged
that authorities will closely monitor the situation in schools and
continue to step [up] prevention.

In Guangdong province, there were 847 cases from January [2011] up to
now. Deputy Director of the Department of Health of Guangdong Province
Huang Fei said the situation in the mainland province [Guangdong
province] is similar to that recorded in both [Macau and Hong Kong]
SARs. "The peak season is in June, more or less the same in the 3
regions. We will continue to conduct studies on prevention and
monitoring," he said.

Hong Kong's DP director further explained that this year's [2011] high
number of cases affected the whole region and refused to talk about an
epidemic in Hong Kong.

"It can be explained by changes in the environment, or immunity was
lower, or germs were stronger. We were already expecting that the
number of cases would rise after the reopening of schools because it
is transmitted human-to-human," Lam said. "But that's not an epidemic;
if it were, we would notify other regions immediately."

[Byline: Alexandra Lages]

